<DOC><DOCNO> AP900730-0142 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-90 1247EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a BC-APIndustryNews 11Takes   07-30 0725</FIRST><SECOND>BC-AP Industry News, 11 Takes,0754</SECOND><HEAD>Publishers</HEAD><HEAD>Editors</HEAD><HEAD>Managing Editors</HEAD><TEXT>   A summary of developments in the news industry for the week ofJuly 23-30:</TEXT><HEAD>Profit Down at Times Mirror, Tribune, Knight-Ridder, WashingtonPost</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Knight-Ridder Inc. reported a 64.8 percent dropin second-quarter earnings, while Times Mirror Co. said itsafter-tax profit tumbled 44.7 percent. Both said the big dropsresulted from comparisons to year-earlier profits that wereinflated by one-time gains from the sale of assets.   In other earnings reports, Tribune Co. said its net profit fell25 percent, and Washington Post Co. said its earnings decreased 7.5percent.   All the companies said their operations were affected by theweakness in the advertising climate.</TEXT><BYLINE>Times Mirror Co.</BYLINE><TEXT>   Times Mirror said it earned $47.0 million in the April-Junequarter, compared with $85.0 million in 1989. Revenue rose 5.3percent to $906.6 million from $861.3 million.   The company said 17 percent of the year-earlier profit came fromthe sale of timberlands.   Robert F. Erburu, chairman and chief executive, said weakeconomic conditions continued to adversely affect the company'snewspaper and other advertising-driven businesses.   For the first six months, the company earned $93.0 million, down39.5 percent from $153.8 million a year earlier. Revenue rose 4percent to $1.78 billion from $1.71 billion.</TEXT><BYLINE>Tribune Co.</BYLINE><TEXT>   Tribune earned $58.1 million in the quarter, compared with $75.3million a year ago. Revenue rose 2 percent to $656.2 million from$643.1 million.   The company said its operating profit from newspaper publishingfell 33 percent, mainly due to losses at the Daily News in NewYork. Profit at the Chicago Tribune improved, but results at itsother papers were flat or lower because of softness in retail andclassified advertising.   Operating profit for the newsprint group fell 83 percent becauseof lower newsprint selling prices and the adverse impact of astronger Canadian dollar.   For the first six months, Tribune earned $89.6 million, down 20percent from $112.1 million in 1989. Revenue rose 3.6 percent to$1.24 billion from $1.2 billion.</TEXT><BYLINE>Knight-Ridder Inc.</BYLINE><TEXT>   Knight-Ridder earned $44.6 million in the quarter, compared with$126.8 million a year earlier. Revenue rose 2.2 percent to $591.7million from $578.7 million.   The company noted that two-thirds of the 1989 profit resultedfrom the sale of the Star News in Pasadena, Calif., and televisionoperations. Net income from continuing operations in the latestquarter was up 14.3 percent from a year ago, it said.   Knight-Ridder said advertising revenue at its 31 newspapers wasunder pressure, with retail and general advertising revenuemarginally higher and classified ad revenue down slightly.   For the first six months, Knight-Ridder earned $70.5 million,down 52 percent from $147.3 million a year earlier. Revenue rose2.7 percent to $1.15 billion from $1.12 billion.</TEXT><BYLINE>Washington Post Co.</BYLINE><TEXT>   Washington Post earned $55.9 million for the quarter, comparedwith $60.5 million a year ago. Revenue edged up 1 percent to $379.6million from $374.5 million.   The company said revenue at its newspaper division dipped 2percent as ad volume fell 9 percent at The Washington Post. Revenueat Newsweek was up 6 percent because the latest quarter had onemore issue than the year-ago period.   Revenue was down 4 percent for the broadcast division and up 11percent in the cable division.   For the first six months, Washington Post earned $95.0 million,down 6.9 percent from $102 million in 1989. Revenue edged up 0.5percent to $720.5 million from $716.3 million.</TEXT><HEAD>Reuters Says Earnings Up 27 Percent</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Reuters Holdings PLC said July 24 that itsafter-tax profit jumped 27 percent in the first half of the year,helped by strong sales in all major markets, particularly Europe.   Reuters said earnings for the January-June period were theequivalent of $188 million, compared with $148 million in 1989.Revenue rose 26 percent to $1.2 billion from $954 million.   The company said sales strength was partly due to the relativeweakness of the pound during the period, which made Britishcompanies more competitive in selling products and services inother countries. The pound has since rebounded.   Reuters said that ``conditions in financial markets remaindifficult and cancellations of Reuter services, which were alreadyhigh, have recently risen further.''   The company did not report separately for the second quarter,which is not required under British law.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>